It is well known that EPS plays a most predominant role in dewatering sludge because of its strong capture of bound water [66]. Thus, the transformations of different EPS fractions were investigated using FRI method. As shown in Fig. 6
                        a, most of organic substances in RS were mainly distributed in TB-EPS, especially in regions I, II, and IV of EEM spectrum, which were widely taken as tyrosine-like, tryptophan-like, and microbial byproduct-like substances [63], respectively. After treatment by SCQDs-PMS system, a considerable proportion of organic substances in TB-EPS were effectively degraded, while its tiny proportion was transformed into substances distributed in regions III and V of EEM spectrum, which were assigned to be fulvic acid-like and humic acid-like substance [63], respectively. The results were well supported by the variations in the concentrations of proteins and polysaccharides in EPS. As shown in Fig. 7
                        a, the total concentrations of proteins and polysaccharides declined from 501.2 and 115.2 mg/L to 150.4 and 86.3 mg/L after conditioning by SCQDs-PMS system, respectively. This phenomenon was also observed in previous studies using SR-AOPs for sludge conditioning [40,42]. Earlier studies have pointed out that tyrosine-like and tryptophan-like substances play predominant role in sludge dewaterability while fulvic acid-like and humic acid-like substances have limited impacts [67–69]. As illustrated in Fig. 6b and 6c, the normalized excitation-emission region volumes (Φi,n
                        ) for regions I and II (i.e., tyrosine-like and tryptophan-like substances) declined significantly from 25.0 × 106 and 23.9 × 106 AU nm2 to 4.4 × 106 and 5.7 × 106 AU nm2 after conditioning by SCQDs-PMS system, respectively, and their corresponding fluorescence response percentages (Pi,n
                        ) had the same decreasing trends. This phenomenon was in good agreement with the significant decreases in the contents of TOC, and SCOD in TB-EPS fraction (Fig. S9e). In addition, the slight increases of Φi,n
                         for regions I, II, III, IV, and V in S-EPS were well in agreement with the obtained contents of TOC and SCOD in S-EPS fraction, which further demonstrated that the effective degradation of TB-EPS could release partial organics and even some intracellular substances to S-EPS due to the oxidation effects of ROS produced in SCQDs-PMS system.
